# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-optimization-web
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] An AVIF file is designed to be a conformant HEIF file for both image items and image sequences.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] Specifically, this specification follows the recommendations given in "Annex I: Guidelines On Defining New Image Formats and Brands" of HEIF.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] This specification reuses syntax and semantics used in the specification for the AV1 Codec ISO Media File Format Binding.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] In tests by Netflix in 2020, AVIF showed better compression efficiency than JPEG, as well as better detail preservation, fewer blocking artifacts and less color bleeding around hard edges in composites of natural images, text, and graphics.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] AVIF has been supported by all major web browsers since 2024, with over 93% of users worldwide on compatible browsers.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] On 14 December 2018, Netflix published the first .avif sample images.
[src:image-optimization-web/avif] In November 2020, HDR sample images with PQ transfer function and BT.2020 color primaries were published.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] It’s been available across browsers since March 2016.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The **`<picture>`** HTML element contains zero or more `<source>` elements and one `<img>` element to offer alternative versions of an image for different display/device scenarios.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The browser will consider each child `<source>` element and choose the best match among them.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] If no matches are found—or the browser doesn't support the `<picture>` element—the URL of the `<img>` element's `src` attribute is selected.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The selected image is then presented in the space occupied by the `<img>` element.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] To decide which URL to load, the user agent examines each `<source>`'s `srcset`, `media`, and `type` attributes to select a compatible image that best matches the current layout and capabilities of the display device.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] It provides a fallback in case none of the offered `<source>` elements are able to provide a usable image.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] If providing higher-density versions of an image for high-DPI (Retina) display, use `srcset` on the `<img>` element instead.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] This lets browsers opt for lower-density versions in data-saving modes, and you don't have to write explicit `media` conditions.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] This element includes only global attributes.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] You can use the `object-position` property to adjust the positioning of the image within the element's frame, and the `object-fit` property to control how the image is resized to fit within the frame.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] These examples demonstrate how different attributes of the `<source>` element change the selection of the image inside `<picture>`.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The `media` attribute specifies a media condition (similar to a media query) that the user agent will evaluate for each `<source>` element.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] If the `<source>`'s media condition evaluates to `false`, the browser skips it and evaluates the next element inside `<picture>`.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The srcset attribute is used to offer a list of possible images based on size or the display's pixel density.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] It is composed of a comma-separated list of image descriptors.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The `srcset` attribute can also be used on the `<img>` element without needing the `<picture>` element.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The `sizes` attribute of the `<source>` element allows you to specify a set of media condition-length pairs and indicate the image display size for each condition.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] This helps the browser select the most appropriate image from the `srcset` attribute, which lists images with their intrinsic widths.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The browser evaluates the media conditions in the sizes attribute before it downloads any images.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] See the sizes attribute of the `<img>` and `<source>` elements for more information.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] Without sizes, the browser will use the default size of the image as specified by its dimensions in pixels.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] This may not be the best fit for all devices, especially if the image is displayed on different screen sizes or in different contexts.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] Please note that sizes will have its effect only if width dimension descriptors are provided with srcset instead of pixel ratio values (200w instead of 2x for example).
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] For more information on using `srcset`, see the Responsive images documentation.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] The `type` attribute specifies a MIME type for the resource URL(s) in the `<source>` element's `srcset` attribute.
[src:image-optimization-web/element-picture] If the user agent does not support the given type, the `<source>` element is skipped.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] In this guide, we'll cover the image file types generally supported by web browsers, and provide insights that will help you select the most appropriate formats to use for your site's imagery.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The image file formats that are most commonly used on the web are listed below.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The following list includes image formats that appear on the web, but which should be avoided for web content (generally this is because either they do not have wide browser support, or because there are better alternatives).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The following sections provide a brief overview of each of the image file types supported by web browsers.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] In the tables below, the term **bits per component** refers to the number of bits used to represent each color component.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For example, an RGB color depth of 8 indicates that each of the red, green, and blue components are represented by an 8-bit value.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] **Bit depth**, on the other hand, is the total number of bits used to represent each pixel in memory.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] APNG is a file format first introduced by Mozilla which extends the PNG standard to add support for animated images.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Conceptually similar to the animated GIF format which has been in use for decades, APNG is more capable in that it supports a variety of color depths, whereas animated GIF supports only 8-bit indexed color.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] APNG is ideal for basic animations that do not need to synchronize to other activities or to a sound track, such as progress indicators, activity throbbers, and other animated sequences.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For example, APNG is one of the formats supported when creating animated stickers for Apple's iMessage application (and the Messages application on iOS).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] They're also commonly used for the animated portions of web browsers' user interfaces.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] AV1 is a coding format that was originally designed for video transmission over the Internet.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The format benefits from the significant advances in video encoding in recent years, and may potentially benefit from the associated support for hardware rendering.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] However it also has disadvantages for some cases, as video and image encoding have some different requirements.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] AVIF does not support progressive rendering, so files must be fully downloaded before they can be displayed.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This often has little impact on real-world user experience because AVIF files are much smaller than the equivalent JPEG or PNG files, and hence can be downloaded and displayed much faster.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For larger file size the impact can become significant, and you should consider using a format that supports progressive rendering.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] AVIF is supported in Chrome, Edge, Opera, Safari and Firefox.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] As support is not yet comprehensive (and has little historical depth) you should provide a fallback in WebP, JPEG or PNG format using the `<picture>` element (or some other approach).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The **BMP** (**Bitmap image**) file type is most prevalent on Windows computers, and is generally used only for special cases in web apps and content.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] BMP theoretically supports a variety of internal data representations.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The simplest, and most commonly used, form of BMP file is an uncompressed raster image, with each pixel occupying 3 bytes representing its red, green, and blue components, and each row padded with `0x00` bytes to a multiple of 4 bytes wide.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] While other data representations are defined in the specification, they are not widely used and often completely unimplemented.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] These features include: support for different bit depths, indexed color, alpha channels, and different pixel orders (by default, BMP is written from bottom-left corner toward the right and top, rather than from the top-left corner toward the right and bottom).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Theoretically, several compression algorithms are supported, and the image data can also be stored in JPEG or PNG format within the BMP file.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] In 1987, the CompuServe online service provider introduced the **GIF** (**Graphics Interchange Format**) image file format to provide a compressed graphics format that all members of their service would be able to use.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] GIF uses the Lempel-Ziv-Welch (LZW) algorithm to losslessly compress 8-bit indexed color graphics.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] GIF was one of the first two graphics formats supported by HTML, along with XBM.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Each pixel in a GIF is represented by a single 8-bit value serving as an index into a palette of 24-bit colors (8 bits each of red, green, and blue).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The length of a color table is always a power of 2 (that is, each palette has 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, or 256 entries).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] To simulate more than 255 or 256 colors, dithering is generally used.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] It is technically possible to tile multiple image blocks, each with its own color palette, to create true color images, but in practice this is rarely done.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Pixels are opaque, unless a specific color index is designated as transparent, in which case pixels colored that value are entirely transparent.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] GIF supports simple animation, in which following an initial full-size frame, a series of images reflecting the parts of the image that change with each frame are provided.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] GIF has been extremely popular for decades, due to its simplicity and compatibility.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Its animation support caused a resurgence in its popularity in the social media era, when animated GIFs began to be widely used for short "videos", memes, and other simple animation sequences.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Another popular feature of GIF is support for interlacing, where rows of pixels are stored out of order so that partially-received files can be displayed in lower quality.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This is particularly useful when network connections are slow.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] GIF is a good choice for simple images and animations, although converting full color images to GIF can result in unsatisfactory dithering.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Typically, modern content should use PNG for lossless *and* indexed still images, and should consider using APNG for lossless animation sequences.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The ICO (Microsoft Windows icon) file format was designed by Microsoft for desktop icons of Windows systems.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] An ICO file can contain multiple icons, and begins with a directory listing details about each.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Following the directory comes the data for the icons.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Each icon's data can be either a BMP image without the file header, or a complete PNG image (including the file header).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] If you use ICO files, you should use the BMP format, as support for PNG inside ICO files wasn't added until Windows Vista and may not be well supported.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The JPEG (typically pronounced "**jay-peg**") image format is currently the most widely used lossy compression format for still images.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] It's particularly useful for photographs; applying lossy compression to content requiring sharpness, like diagrams or charts, can produce unsatisfactory results.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] JPEG is actually a data format for compressed photos, rather than a file type.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The JFIF (**J**PEG **F**ile **I**nterchange **F**ormat) specification describes the format of the files we think of as "JPEG" images.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The PNG (pronounced "**ping**") image format uses lossless compression, while supporting higher color depths than GIF and being more efficient, as well as featuring full alpha transparency support.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] PNG is widely supported, with all major browsers offering full support for its features.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] SVG is an XML-based vector graphics format that specifies the contents of an image as a set of drawing commands that create shapes, lines, apply colors, filters, and so forth.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] SVG files are ideal for diagrams, icons, and other images which can be accurately drawn at any size.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] As such, SVG is popular for user interface elements in modern Web design.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] SVG files are text files containing source code that, when interpreted, draws the desired image.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] An SVG image can be embedded in HTML using elements such as `<iframe>`, `<object>` and `<embed>`.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] It is possible to use SVG images anywhere where other image types can be used, including with the `<img>` element, the `background-image` CSS property, and so forth.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] However, there are additional restrictions when SVG is used in this way.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] SVG is an ideal choice for images which can be represented using a series of drawing commands, especially if the size at which the image will be rendered is unknown or may vary, since SVG will smoothly scale to the desired size.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] It's not generally useful for strictly bitmap or photographic images, although it is possible to include bitmap images within an SVG.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] TIFF is a raster graphics file format which was created to store scanned photos, although it can be any kind of image.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] It is a somewhat "heavy" format, in that TIFF files have a tendency to be larger than images in other formats.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This is because of the metadata often included, as well as the fact that most TIFF images are either uncompressed or use compression algorithms that still leave fairly large files after compression.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] TIFF supports a variety of compression methods, but the most commonly used are the CCITT Group 4 (and, for older fax systems, Group 3) compression systems used for by fax software, as well as LZW and lossy JPEG compression.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This allows different data types to be used for the same properties.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For example, the width of an image, `ImageWidth`, is stored using tag `0x0100`, and is a one-entry array.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] A single TIFF file can contain multiple images; this may be used to represent multi-page documents, for example (such as a multi-page scanned document, or a received fax).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] However, software reading TIFF files is only required to support the first image.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] TIFF supports a variety of color spaces, not just RGB.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] These include CMYK, YCbCr, and others, making TIFF a good choice for storing images intended for print, film, or television media.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Other than Safari, browsers do not natively support TIFF images in web content except by using special libraries or browser add-ons.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] As such, TIFF files are not broadly used for displaying web content, *but* it's common to provide downloadable TIFF files when distributing photos and other artwork intended for precision editing or printing.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] WebP supports lossy compression via predictive coding based on the VP8 video codec, and lossless compression that uses substitutions for repeating data.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Lossy WebP images are on average 25–35% smaller than JPEG images of visually similar compression levels.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Lossless WebP images are typically 26% smaller than the same images in PNG format.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] WebP also supports animation: in a lossy WebP file, the image data is represented by a VP8 bitstream, which may contain multiple frames.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Lossless WebP holds the `ANIM` chunk, which describes the animation, and the `ANMF` chunk, which represents a frame of an animation sequence.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] WebP now has broad support in the latest versions of major web browsers, although it does not have deep historical support.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Provide a fallback in either JPEG or PNG format, such as with the `<picture>` element.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] XBM (X Bitmap) files were the first to be supported on the Web, but are no longer used and should be avoided, as their format has potential security concerns.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Modern browsers have not supported XBM files in many years, but when dealing with older content, you may find some still around.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] XBM uses a snippet of C code to represent the contents of the image as an array of bytes.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Each image consists of 2 to 4 `#define` directives, providing the width and height of the bitmap (and optionally the hotspot, if the image is designed as a cursor), followed by an array of `unsigned char`, where each value contains 8 1-bit monochrome pixels.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] The image must be a multiple of 8 pixels wide.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Picking the best image format for your needs is likely easier than video formats, as there are fewer options with broad support, and each tends to have a specific set of use-cases.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Photographs typically fare well with lossy compression (depending on the encoder's configuration).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This makes JPEG and WebP good choices for photographs, with JPEG being more compatible but WebP perhaps offering better compression.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] To maximize quality and minimize download time, consider providing both using a fallback with WebP as the first choice and JPEG as the second.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Otherwise, JPEG is the safe choice for compatibility.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For smaller images such as icons, use a lossless format to avoid loss of detail in a size-constrained image.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] While lossless WebP is ideal for this purpose, support is not widespread yet, so PNG is a better choice unless you offer a fallback.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] If your image contains fewer than 256 colors, GIF is an option, although PNG often compresses even smaller with its indexed compression option (PNG-8).
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] If the icon can be represented using vector graphics, consider SVG, since it scales across various resolutions and sizes, so it's perfect for responsive design.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Although SVG support is good, it may be worth offering a PNG fallback for older browsers.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Unless you're willing to compromise on quality, you should use a lossless format for screenshots.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] This is particularly important if there's any text in your screenshot, as text easily becomes fuzzy and unclear under lossy compression.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] PNG is probably your best bet, but lossless WebP is arguably going to be better compressed.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] For any image that can be represented using vector graphics, SVG is the best choice.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] Otherwise, you should use a lossless format like PNG.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] If you do choose a lossy format, such as JPEG or lossy WebP, carefully weigh the compression level to avoid causing text or other shapes to become fuzzy or unclear.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] While the standard HTML `<img>` element doesn't support compatibility fallbacks for images, the `<picture>` element does.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] `<picture>` is used as a wrapper for a number of `<source>` elements, each specifying a version of the image in a different format or under different media conditions, as well as an `<img>` element which defines where to display the image and the fallback to the default or "most compatible" version.
[src:image-optimization-web/formats-image-types] You can specify as many `<source>`s as you wish, though typically 2 or 3 is all you need.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Image compression may be lossy or lossless.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Lossless compression is preferred for archival purposes and often for medical imaging, technical drawings, clip art, or comics.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Lossy compression methods, especially when used at low bit rates, introduce compression artifacts.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Lossy methods are especially suitable for natural images such as photographs in applications where minor (sometimes imperceptible) loss of fidelity is acceptable to achieve a substantial reduction in bit rate.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Lossy compression that produces negligible differences may be called visually lossless.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] The quality of a compression method often is measured by the peak signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] It measures the amount of noise introduced through a lossy compression of the image, however, the subjective judgment of the viewer also is regarded as an important measure, perhaps, being the most important measure.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Entropy coding started in the late 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was published in 1952.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] An important development in image data compression was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] JPEG was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] JPEG was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed by Abraham Lempel, Jacob Ziv and Terry Welch in 1984.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm developed by Phil Katz and specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was developed from 1997 to 2000 by a JPEG committee chaired by Touradj Ebrahimi (later the JPEG president).
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] It uses the CDF 9/7 wavelet transform (developed by Ingrid Daubechies in 1992) for its lossy compression algorithm, and the Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 wavelet transform (developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] Tabatabai in 1988) for its lossless compression algorithm.
[src:image-optimization-web/image-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
